{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_adamsmorgan_ver01/data/sn84026749/00222254681/1930021901/0070.xml":{"full_text":"2\n\u201cWHO ORDERED \u2018GREEN HAT\u2019 LIQUOR?\u201d SEN. JONES ASKS\nWILL GET NAME\nBADOKHART\nASSERTS\n(Continued from Page 1.)\nwaited for Goldberg at the east\nend of the Senate Office Build\ning yesterday afternoon at 3:30\no\u2019clock. They had been informed\nt\u00bbat he was to deliver a number\nof quarts of gin by placing them\nIn a parked car near the building.\nWhen they went to arrest Gold\nberg, he threw the bottles, which\nwere wrapped up in a package,\nbreaking all of them on the side\nwalk, the agents reported. A gill\nof alleged liquor was recovered\nfor a sample, however, and Gold\nberg and a girl, Ida Deckelbaum,\nwho was with him at the time,\nwere arrested.\nThey were taken to the Sixth\nprecinct and both charged. As\nsistant District Attorney Shea re\nfused papers on the Deckelbaum\ngirl, however.\nCassidy is said to have had six\nfluarts of liquor at the time of his\n\u25a0arrest, a few hours earlier, almost\nIn the sarfle spot. Both Cassidy\nand Goldberg are at liberty on\n$2,000 bond each.\nThese undercover men are at\nwork scrubbing floors in the\nSenate Office Building, and doing\nodd chores in the corridors and\noffices, it was reported today.\n'They have been on this detail for\nmore than a week, it is said.\nSenator Wheeler (D.) of Mon\ntana, who sponsored a resolution\nfor a sweeping senatorial inquiry\ninto all activities of the Prohibi\ntion Bureau, declared the actions\nof the \u201cMan in the Green Hat\u201d\nought to be investigated.\nWants Customer Named\nSenator Jones (R.) of Wash\nington, author of the \u201cFive and\nTen\u201d law, went further and said\nthe Senate ought to learn \u201cwho\u201d\nCassidy intended to see in the\nSenate Office Building. The\nstructure houses the private offi\nces of Senators and their hun\ndreds of clerks.\n\u201cThis episode ought to be the\nsubject of a Senate inquiry,\u201d said\nWheeler. \u201cIt is one more reason\nwhy the Senate ought to investi\ngate prohibition enforcement and\nits enforceability.\u201d\n\u201cThere evidently is something\nwrong,\u201d said Senator Jones, refer\nring to the fact that Cassidy has\ntwice been arrested in front of the\nSenate Office Building. \u201cIt\nought to be brought out, if pos\nsible, why he was going there and\nwhom he intended to see.\u201d\n\u201cI\u2019m glad to hear about it.\u2019'\nobserved Senator Brookhart (R.>\nof lowa.\nBrookhart to Get It\n\u201cAre you going to suggest an\ninvestigation to learn who is buy\ning booze from him?\u201d Brookhart\nwas asked.\n\u201cOh\u2019 we\u2019re going to have that,\u201d\nreplied the lowan.\nSenator Watson (R.) of In\ndiana, interposed an objection\nto such an inquiry.\n\u201cI\u2019m not seeking to guard the\nmorals of my fellow Senators,\nsaid Watson. \u201cThat\u2019s their busi\nness and the business of their\nconstituents.\u201d\nM'GARRTNGASE\nBEFORE BOARD\nI\n(Continued from Page 1.)\nSullivan said he took out of Mc-\nCarrom\u2019s car, just after the crash.\nSullivan said he had sent them\nto a Government chemist for\nanalysis.\n\u201cWhat did the analysis show?\u201d\nasked Stott.\nSullivan fidgeted and said \u201cI\nreally have not heard,\u201d\n\u201cI would like very much to\nknow whether McCarrom*s condi\ntion was caused by alcohol or\nfrom stupor caused by some other\nconcotion,\u201d said Stott.\n\u201cDoes anybody know the re\nault of this analysis,\u201d he asked\nthe room in general.\nNo one knew.\nInspector Albert J. Headly, who\nwith Lieutenant Sullivan, arrested\nMcCarron just after the accident,\nsaid the officer seemed to he in\ntoxicated and was \u201cmore or less\nbeligerant.\u201d Headley added, how\never, that McCarron was able to\n\u201cnavigate\u201d on his feet but he did\nnot believe him capable of dric\ning a car safety.\nThe inspector said he would\nnot have arrested a civilian who\n\u2022was only intoxicated to that ex\ntent if he met him on the street.\n2 Dead Soldiers Sent\nTo Wrong Widows\nCHICAGO. Feb. 19 (1.N.5.).\u2014\nBy a whimsical trick of fate, the\nbodies of two World War veterans,\nwho succumbed to battle wounds\nafter 11 years, were being ex\nchanged today by two towns 600\nmiles apart. An undertaker had\nmistaken the bodies and sent\nthem to the wrong towns for\nburial.\nIn Murphyboro, Hl., members of\nthe American Legion had gath\nered to bestow the last rites upon\ntheir comrade, William E. Wag-\nPEOPLE\nWho Interest\nYou and\nthe Things\nThey Do\nTwo Pretty Film Stars\nGet Divorce Decrees\nLOS ANGELES, Feb. 19\n(IN.S.).\u2014In less than five min\nutes yesterday two film stars\n\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0l were granted\ndecrees of di\n\u25a0FT?? vorce from\np Ihe 1 r hus\nbands in tWO\nI separate su\nperior courts.\n081 WA Mildred Har-\nH^K s fl ris. former\nwife of Chas.\nChaplin, ob\ntalned he r di\nA W vorce from\nX*' Everett Ter-\nJlre.-- S rance Mac\nGovern in\nthree minutes\nMII.DKKD HARRIS when she ap\npeared before Superior Judge\nHarry R. Archbald.\nTwo minutes later, Superior\nJudge Frank C. .Collier signed\nan order freeing Maria Corda,\nHungarian actress, from her di\nrector husband, Alexander\nCorda.\nMiss Corda, who has experi\nenced a rather up and down\ncareer in pictures, was given\n\u00a3er first op-\nportunity in\nhe film ver- JT\u2019\nion of John MflflLLil\nErskine\u2019s\n\u201cThe Private\nLife of Helen\nof Troy,\u201d but\nthe picture fl\nfailed and she MUJK\nhas since re- fl* aL?\ntrograded to\nthe rank and\nfile of poten\ntial stars,\nmany of\nwhom, like W IfgP'\nMiss Corda, maria corda\nwere ruled from success by the\nquick rise of talking pictures.\nThe fortunes of Mildred Har\nris have been quite as quixotic,\nher chief business in the past\ntwo years being vaudeville.\nWith its slow decline, she\nhas made no attempt at a film\ncomeback.\nSmuts, Home, Tells\nof Walks With King\nCAPE TOWN, South Africa,\nFeb. 19.\u2014Gen. Jan Christian\nSmuts, former prime minister\nof South Africa and now leader\n\u25a0BPPPMMpgB of tbe opposi\n\u25a0mf MB tion party,\nwas tendered\nb an enthusias-\n1 tic rece Ption\nMill bere on bls\nI return from\nK B an extended\nflflOi:: fl visit to Great\n'\"fl Britain. Can-\nada and tbc\nUnited States.\nG e n e r a 1\nSmuts told of\nthe improve\nments in the\nhealth of\nGeneral Smote King George,\nwhich he noted on his visit to\nthe latter at Sandringham, Nor\nfolk. He had walked with the\nKing for hours and the latter\nseemed not the least fatigued,\nhe said.\nBaden-Powell Inspects\nBermuda Boy Scouts\nHAMILTON, Bermuda, Feb.\n19.\u2014Lord Baden-Powell, known\nas the father of the Boy Scout\nmovement in\nGreat\u00dfritain,\nis here in-\nspecting Ber- Jg\nmuda troups fl\nof Boy Scouts. j\nA delegation\nof Scouts met\nLord and\nLady Baden- f\nPowell at the\npier when\nthey arrived grPgF\nin Bermuda X?/\nTuesday\nmorning. im-X'\nBaden-Pow-\nell won mili- baden-powell\ntary honors in the Boer War\nwhen he defended Ladysmith,\nbesieged by the Boers for over\n100 days.\nTwo Wedding Permits\nIssued at Rockville\nROCKVILLE, Md.. Feb. 19.\u2014\nMarriage licenses have been is\nsued here to the following:\nArmand F. Bergman, 31, Chevy\nChase, Md\u201e and Phoebe M. Cran\ndall, 24, Wayville, N. Y.\nVirgil E. McDaniel, 28, and\nDorothy E. Blue, 18, both of Clar\nendon, Va.\nner, 40. who died in Edward\nHines, Jr., Memorial Hospital\nhere.\nIn Ulrichsville, Ohio, another\ngroup paid homage to John W.\nPhillips at a burial ceremony\nHe also died in the Government\nhospital here.\nBoth widows, looking upon the\nopen caskets fainted upon seeing\nthe face of a stranger. Services\nwere thrown into confusion.\nQuiet was restored and an in\nvestigation launched.\nTHE WASHINGTON TIMES\nLEHLBACH BILL\nGETS BACKING\nIN BOARD\n(Continued from Page 1.)\nliquor?\u201d asked one member of\nCongress after he had sat around\nfor 10 minutes or so listening to\nthe remarks of Stewart. He, with\nothers, was directed to go down\nthe hall to the regular meeting\nroom, on the same floor, of the\nHouse Judiciary Committee.\nStatistics Given\nAll the earlier testimony today\nbefore the Civil Service Commit\ntee was in advocacy of new Lehi\nbach retirement bill.\nPreceding /Stewart on the stand\nwere U. G. Biller, statistician of\nthe Pension Bureau, who com\npleted his testimony begun late\nyesterday afternoon; Frank G.\nAshbrook, a biologist in the De\nportment of Agriculture, and L.\nO. Robbins, also of the Depart\nment of Agriculture, who supplied\nmany figures indicating their\npreference for the Lehlbach bill\nas compared with the original\nlaw.\nRobbins suggested an amend\nment to the pending bill, under\nwhich any employe of the Gov\nernment at the age of 60 years,\nand after 30 years of service,\nmight apply for voluntary re\ntirement.\nRobbins said he had been in\nthe Department of Agriculture\nfor 31 years and was now draw\ning a salary of $3,500.\nNot Ready to Quit\nThe group he represented, he\ntold the committee, would like to\nsee an amendment authorizing\nvoluntary retirement at the age\nof 60, although Robbins, with a\ngrin on his face, said he would\nlike to work for the Government\nuntil he became the age of 72\nor 75 or thereabouts.\nNevertheless, Mr. Robbins said,\nthe average man who has worked\nfor the Government for 30 years\nor more and has reached the\nage of 60 \u201chas sorter lost his\ngrip, slowed down, burned out\u201d\nand he ought to have a chance\nto retire voluntarily if he wants\nto do it. He concluded that the\nmost difficult personnel problem\nof the Government is to take\ncare of old men and women who\nhave \u201cslowed down.\u201d\n\u201cThere is a suggestion always,\"\nsaid Robbins, \u201cthat when one\ngets old in the service he must\ntake a smaller job at less pay.\nBut that is humiliating and few\nwould do it. I\u2019d like to see\nCongress enact some law to take\ncare of these old-timers.\u201d\nStewart gave a long disserta\ntion on the Federal retirement\nproposal and, getting back to the\nLehlbach bill, said that \u201cthis biil\ncommits the Government for the\nfirst time to its fair proportion\nof the cost of retirement of its\nsuperannuated employes.\u201d\nIt is the start, he said, of a\nreal set up between the Govern\nment and its employes and that\nit should be enacted.\nSTATE CONTROL\nOF RUM ASKED\n(Continued from Page 1.)\nof every one of your States and\nbelieve that every one of your\nrepresent a State worthy of hav\ning returned it to her discretion\nto deal with her own matters.\u201d\nStayton told the committee \u201cit\nis significant that the Anti-saloon\nLeague has discontinued publish\ning statistics of arrests for drunk\nenness.\u201d\nThe league\u2019s blue book showed\nincreases in arrests from 300,000\nin 1919 to 423,000 fpr drunken\nness in 1923, he said.\n\u201cThey have not published sta\ntistics\u2014it must be that they are\nnot satisfying,\u201d he said. i\nCol. Grayson M. P. Murphy, a\nNew York banker, director of the\nBethlehem Steel and Goodyear\nRubber companies, adjutant gen\neral of the Rainbow Division of\nthe A. E. F., was the first spokes\nman for \u201cbig business.\u201d\n\u201cAfter a long struggle I have\ncome to the belief that the peo\nple should realize the danger m\nthe situation, abolish prohibition\nand promote temperance,\u201d ne\nsaid.\nPropose Compromise\nRepresentative Linthicum of\nMaryland announced that he\ntween the proposal of Mrs. Mary\nT. Norton. Democratic Congress\nwoman from New Jersey, for a\nnational referendum, and the\nresolution of Representative Sab\nath (D.) of Illinois, to adopt a\nnew amendment giving Congress\ncomplete control of the liquor\ntraffic subject to a veto by dry\nStates on liquor within their own\nborders.\n\u201cI challenge the drys to agree\nto a national referendum on pro\nhibition, with the substitute plan\nwhich would leave Congress in\ncontrol of the situation.\u201d said\nLinthicum.\nHIGH PLUNGE TO DEATH\nCHICAGO, Feb. 19 (1.N.5.).\u2014\nWilliam L. Lowenberg, a De\ntroit salesman, leaped to his\ndeath yesterday from the eight\neenth floor of the Lake Michigan\nBuilding. He left a note asking\nthat his body be cremated.\nVeteran Freed of Perjury Charge\nJEL\nk. \u25a0\u2019Wk.\nMi\nfl W r JlCi\u00ae\nIW- I i\nI 'I mrjHl\n\u2014Tim?* Staff Photo\nWILLIAM J. SULLIVAN FRANK R. SWAN L. W. WHITESTONE\nJUSTICE PEYTON GORDON directed a jury in Criminal Court yesjterday to\nreturn a verdict of acquittal in the case of the United States Government against\nFrank R. Swan, accused of perjury. The case developed from Swann\u2019s application\nto the Veterans\u2019 Bureau for a duplicate compensation certificate, declaring the origi\nnal lost after it had been given to his wife, since divorced, for keeping. The wife\u2019s\nstory could not be substantiated.\nMANY ADDICTS\nIN DISTRICT\n(Continued from Page 1.)\nbegan writing his own prescrip\ntions. Three years after he had\nbecome an addict he was de\nbarred from the medical profes\nsion. His family and medical\nfriends are now attempting to\ncure him by confinement.\nAnother instance is that of a\nwoman, well dressed and of ap\nparent refinement, who is known\nto dozens of practitioners through\nher efforts to secure narcotics by\nsubterfuge.\nA pharmacist in a store in a\nfashionable apartment house on\nMassachusetts Avenue where the\ndoctor maintains his offices, was\ncalled in and asked for his\nopinion.\n\u201cTo say thousands would be a\nconservative estimate,\u201d he said.\nHe recalled the numbers of at\ntempts to secure dope which had\nbeen made while he was em\nployed for years in several down\ntown stores.\nTo the question\u2014\u201c What hap\npens when a person of education\nand position in life falls into the\ndope habit?\u201d\u2014the doctor replied:\nThe physical effect of slight ad\ndiction is comparatively negligible.\nWhat happens is a more or less\ncomplete breakdown of moral\nfiber. Morphine, for instance, af\nfects certain brain cells. Long\nafter the immediate stimulation\nhas worn off, it leaves them de\npressed and paralyzed.\nCasualty Has New Ambulance\nEHBBB SB -IB I\ni\nIJm IbJr'B 1 Ji\nBBH| jjgy\nnHi BBb\n\u2014Times Staff Photo\nHUMANITARIAN VEHICLE PUT IN USE\nHERE ARE Dr. Louis Jimal, with two of Casualty' Hospital\u2019s nurses. Misses\nAngela Winters and Annette Day, together with the new ambulance which the institution\nhas just put into service. L I\nTke Httirnd Dedly\nMalone Wants Fame\nAs \u201cReconciliation\u201d\nLawyer\nNEW YORK, Feb. 19 (IN.S.)\nDudley Field Malone, internation\nally known divorce lawyer, re\nturned from Europe today with\nhis bride, the former Edna John\nson, of Brooklyn. They were mar\nried in London a few weeks ago.\nMalone told reporters he would\nlike to be known as \u201cthe well\nknown reconciliation lawyer.\u201d\n\u201cI\u2019m getting tired of being\ncalled a divorce lawyer,\u201d he said.\n\u201cI\u2019ve effected more reconcilia\ntions than divorces\u2014far more.\nMalone was divorced last year\nfrom Doris Stevens, author and\nfeminist leader.\nLocal Plant. Is First\nIn Safety Campaign\nD. J. Gibson, manager of the\nGeneral Baking Company\u2019s Wash\nington plant. 119 First St. S. W.,\nannounced today that the Wash\nington plant had finished in first\nplace in a nationwide safety al\nways campaign, conducted during\nthe past 12 months among the 50\nplants of the General Baking\nCompany.\nIn recognition of Washington\u2019s\nsuccess, the plant has been pre\nsented a silver trophy.\nThe Washington plant, which\noperated its delivery equipment\nand manufacturing departments\nfor 10 months without a single\naccident, also won the group\ncontest in which it competed\nagainst other General Baking\nCompany plants in Philadelphia,\nReading, Norfolk and Allentown.\nNow durlnir the Midwinter Teed\nCar Shows in the time to buy a\nearn. See the lintlnrs In Time* I:uml\nfled Ade.\nWEDNESDAY, FEBRUARY I\u00ae, 1080\nBLIND SENATOR\nSCORNS PITY\n(Continued from Page 1.)\nhelped him in preparing his\ncases, and read and reread the\nessential parts so that he could\nmemorize them and know to\nwhat authorities to refer to, and\nf to quote them as well as to tell\nwhere they could be found. 4\n\u201cPeople will trust a blind man,\nif he has ability, just as quick as\na man with sight,\u201d Senator Schall\nI continued. \u201cI worked along in\ndarkness a good deal harder than\nwhen I had my sight. I had to.\nIn fact, a blind man\u2019s mind rests\nonly when he sleeps, since he\n1 must feel with it and see with it\n\u2014ever on guard, alert, for the\nlittle indirect thing that will guide\nhim to the conclusion that he\nmust have in order to cope with\nthe seeing.\n\u201cAfter 21 years of darkness, I\nwouldn\u2019t trade the understanding\ni j that has come to me for all the\neyes in the world. I entered the\nforest of darkness untamed, un\ndisciplined, grasping, selfish. I\ncame out of that darkness when\nunderstanding became my sight,\nwhen I learned to bear dis\nappointment, when I had compre\nhended that the thing was done\nfor love of the cause and not\nfor self-aggrandizement. I be\ncame interested unselfishly, and\nworked because the work was\nthere to be done, without con\nsidering whether the result would\nhelp me or not.\u201d\ni Schall was blinded by an elec\n-1 trie shock he suffered at the age\nof 30.\nFEW FARMS\nBETTER, EDISON\nSUGGESTS\n(Continued from Page 1.)\nthe towns and took up manufac\nturing.\n\"What do you think of the\nbusiness outlook?\u201d was one ques\ntion put to the inventor of the\nelectric light, the phonograph, the\nmotion picture camera and nu\nmerous other devices.\n\u201cI think it will come out all\nright,\u201d Edison replied optimisti\ncally. \u201cOur only trouble is ex\ncesses\u2014overdoing things.\u201d\n\u201cDid we overdo in the specula\nting in stocks in Wall Street?\u201d\nOverdid Speculation\n\u201cYes, and we overdo in every\nthing else.\u201d\n\u201cDoes business need any one\nparticular thing more brains,\nmore hard work, or what?\u201d he\nwas asked.\n\u201cMore highly organized brains,\u201d\nEdison answered promptly, add\ning: \u201cYet this country seems\nto have a large number of men\nwith brains.\u201d\n\u201cHave you ever seen the coun\ntry in better shape than at pres\nent?\u201d\n\u201cNo, I never have.\u201d\n\u201cWhat per cent of America's\nvast resources are being used, in\nyour opinion?\u201d\n\u201cI should say 5 per cent,\u201d re\nplied Edison, after a pause.\nThe present \u201cmachine age\u201d in\nwhich we are living is helping\nthe world \u201cvery much,\u201d according\nto Edison, and he expressed the\nopinion that eventually machines\nwill do away with man power.\nHe said man power will be sup\nplanted by brain power.\nEdison suddenly launched into\na discussion of the farm and\nthe manufacturing situations, de\ndaring:\nFarms Over Produce\n\u201cWe have too many people in\nthe farm business. We have\n120.000,000 stomachs to feed in\nthis country. The demand for\nthings to fill that number of\nstomachs is necessarily limited.\nThe farms, however, produce\nmore than sufficient to fill these\nstomachs. The result is the farmer\ndoes not make a profit because\nhe over-produces.\n\u201cOn the other hand the de\nmand for what the manufacturers\nproduce is unlimited. .Therefore\nmore people should come off the\nfarms and go into the towns and\nmanufacture things tha* are in\nunlimited demand.\u201d\nEdison is convinced, he said,\nthat prohibition is here to stay.\nHe thinks the laboring man\nshould not expect to \u201chave every\nthing,\u201d especially alcohol which\n\u201cbefuddles his brain.\u201d He be\nlieves the dry law is helping the\ncountry, economically.\nThe aged inventor seemed to be\nvery happy as he worked away\nat his bench in the low, green\nwooden laboratory on his estate.\nThe shelves were lined with\nbottles such as you see in a drug\nstore and men were busy filling\nand refilling vials with various\nkinds of fluid. Outside, among\nthe rubber plants, men were\nbusy caring for them. Plants\narrived daily from all parts of the\ncountry.\nEdison goes to work each morn\ning at 9 o\u2019clock. Mrs. Edison,\nan attractive middle aged woman\nwith gray hair and luminous\ndark brown eyes, accompanies\nhim from his home to the gate\nwhich leads across the roadway\nto the part of the estate which\nharbors the laboratory. She always\nsends him to work with a word\nof cheer. Invariably there is a\ngroup of tourists waiting with\ncameras and they \u201csnap\u201d the\nfamous inventor as, walking\nstick in hand, he slowly trudges\nacross the street, through a\ngate which is always guarded\nand on to his beloved laboratory.\nFire Department Has\nPlaces for Applicants\nThe Civil Service Commission\nhas announced that it will re\nceive applications for the position\nof private in the Washington fire\ndepartment until March 18.\nAge limits in the position are\n21 and 31 years, and the entrance\nsalary is SI,BOO per year.\nGold Strike \u2019ls Called\nRichest in 30 Years\nWhat is believed to be the\nrichest gold \u201cfind\u201d in 30 years is\ncontained in the Pilgrim Mine,\nMohave county, Ariz.\nM. B. Dudley and Varro Peter\nson, joint owners of the mine,\nwho are now in Washington on\nbusiness, declare that an opening\nof 2,000 feet along the surface\nof the ground has exposed a vein\nof the precMus metal which is\nworth more than $2,000,000, and\nthere is more of the one not yet\nuncovered. z\nSamples of the ore which Dud\nley and Peterson have with them\nare said to contain a large per\ncentage of gold, even the poorest\nore assaying around $2,000 to\nthe ton.\nDwight E. Woodbridge, mining\nexpert of Duluth, Minn., a recog\nnized authority on mines, is\nN HAL PARLEY\nCHIEFS PLAN\nTO RECESS\n(Continued from Pogo 1.)\nwith President Gaston Doumer\ngue, presumably to discuss the\npossibility of his attempting to\nform a new cabinet.\nAfter a half an hour\u2019s consul\ntation with the President, how\never, M. Tardieu would admit\nonly that he \u201chad outlined the\nsituation at London for the\nbenefit of the President.\"\nNevertheless the conference\nwas regarded as significantly in\ndicating that M. Tardieu had\nbeen asked whether or not he\nwould be willing to form a cab\ninet to succeed his. old govern\nment.\nThere appeared to be little\nchance today that a new govern\nment could be formed before the\nend of this week.\nSince the fall of the Tardieu\ngovernment Monday night as a\nresult of radical Socialist opposi\ntion to its internal financial\npolicy. President Gaston Dou\nmergue has made little progress\nin the solution of the govern\nmental crisis.\nBecause of ill-health, former\nPremier Poincare eliminated him\nself from the running during a\nconference with the president yes\nterday. Aristide Briand, veteran\nleader of many ministries, was\naverse to being called upon to\nform a cabinet for similar rea\nsons. Senator Etienne Clemcntel,\na left leader who has been prom\ninently mentioned, also has indi\ncated he does not want to make\nthe attempt.\nThis leaves M. Tardieu still in\nthe fore as the most logical man\nto head the next government,\nTardieu, however, is reported to\nbe adamant in his desire to hold\nto the financial policy which\nbrought about his downfall.\nPROSE RMTE\nON CHARGES\n(Continued from Page 1.)\nthe result of testimony of City\nEditor O\u2019Connell, who when first\ncalled to the witness'stand in the\ntrial' of Detective Langdon was\nasked by counsel to outline a\nconversation he had with the\nCommissioner of Prohibition.\nO\u2019Connell\u2019s reply was to the\neffect that The Times had been\ngathering prohibition information\nfor about a month and had a list\nof \u201csomewhere between seven and\nten members of the Metropolitan\nPolice Department who, according\nto the information given to us,\nhad been engaged in some sort\nof way in violation of the prohibi\ntin act.\u201d\nHe was interrupted after he\nhad enumerated two captains and\none lieutenant.\nThe office of the United States\nAttorney understands that infor\nmation by The Times last Octo\nber was insufficient at that time\nto procure Indictments against\nany of the policemen and would\nbe less sufficient at this time and\naction by the Grand Jury would\nonly consume ah unjustifiable\namount of that body\u2019s valuable\ntime.\nHowever, the edtiors have sig\nnified their willingness to appear\nahd give what information they\npossessed up to the time of Lang\ndon\u2019s arrest, should they be called\nupon to do so, but it is considered\nby the authorities that the ef\nforts put forth at this time would\nnot justify the results.\nChinese Nationalists\nDefeat Rebel Troops\nLONDON, Feb. 19 (IN.S.).\u2014A\nthree-day battle between National\nist and Rebel troops north of\nCanton resulted in a terrific de\nfeat for the latter, according to\nan Exchange Telegraph dispatch\nreceived from Hong Kong today.\nThe Nationalists captured 1,000\ntroops and 2,000 rifles, the dis\npatch stated. The Rebels then\nretreated to Kwei-Shien where\nthey were defeated in another\nbattle.\nquoted as having predicted that\nthe Pilgrim mine will probably\nbe one of the greatest gold dis\ncoveries of recent years. He\nstates that, while it is impossible\nto say how much the mine will\nprove to be worth, there is every\npossibility that it will run as high\nas $10,000,000.\nThe Pilgrim mine has been\nworked for about 25 years, but it\nis only recently that the big\n\u201cstrike\u201d was made. It was first\nopened to a depth of 350 feet by\nJohn Brookman, and passed\nthrough several hands before Dud\nley and Peterson took it over\nabout a year ago.\nDudley is an \u201cold-timer\u201d in the\ngold-mining business, having par\nticipated in the Klondike and at\nGoldfield. Nev., and also founded\nthe Hilltop, Nev., mine.\n4\ni","height":"30534","width":"24306"}}
